# Purpose

Enforce test structure and tooling for frontend component and unit tests.

# Rules

## Tooling

- Vitest + `@testing-library/react` + jsdom
- Vitest globals (`describe`, `it`, `expect`, `vi`, etc.) configured in `vite.config.ts`

## Component Tests

- Co-locate test file next to component: `Button.tsx` → `Button.test.tsx`
- Use `render`, `screen`, and `userEvent` from `@testing-library/react`.
- Test user-visible behavior. DO NOT test implementation details (internal state, refs, private methods).
- Assert on what the user sees (text, roles, aria attributes) and what happens on interaction.

```typescript
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event';
import { describe, expect, it, vi } from 'vitest';
import Button from './Button';

describe('Button', () => {
    it('renders label', () => {
        render(<Button label="Submit" type="button" />);
        expect(screen.getByText('Submit')).toBeInTheDocument();
    });

    it('does not fire onClick when isLoading', async () => {
        const onClick = vi.fn();
        render(<Button label="Submit" type="button" isLoading onClick={onClick} />);
        await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button'));
        expect(onClick).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
    });
});
```

## Unit Tests

- Co-locate next to the module under test: `utils.ts` → `utils.test.ts`
- Test pure functions and utilities in isolation.
- DO NOT render components in unit tests — use component tests for that.

## Required Commands

```bash
cd frontend
npm test           # Vitest (watch mode)
npm run type-check # tsc --noEmit
```

# Anti-Patterns

- DO NOT test internal component state — test rendered output and user interactions.
- DO NOT use `test.only` or `it.skip` in committed code.
- DO NOT share mutable state between `it` blocks — reset with `beforeEach`.

# Checklist

- [ ] Test file co-located: `<Component>.test.tsx` next to `<Component>.tsx`
- [ ] Assertions target visible output and user interactions
- [ ] No `test.only` or `it.skip` in committed tests
- [ ] `npm test` passes
